<br>
I agree with you Valquiss...EQ is basically Quake or Doom with longer fights, more power-ups and a thread of continuity.  <br>
<br>
Despite disagreeing with you on another topic Robin Goodfellow, I totally agree with you on the decline of RPG's.  I played AD&amp;D, GURPS, Shadowrun and a lot of other pen and paper games for years - with many folks who play EQ with me now as a matter of fact.  And I tend to believe that the new generations since I became involved in RPG's have too many other distractions to get involved with that are MUCH easier to follow.<br>
<br>
Pen and paper games forced you to *gasp* read a set of rulebooks and *shudder* write out your character/dungeon/campaign ideas on paper and *faint* exercise your imagination!?!?!?  Now, everything is prepackaged and microwaveable.<br>
<br>
I have a good analogy:  I went to buy a younger cousin a Christmas present and thought I'd get him a Lego &quot;set&quot;...you know, a big package of various pieces of Lego with which he could exercise his creativity.  I went to Wal-Mart (shudder) and what did I find?  Well, it wasn't a generic Lego set.  Rather, Lego is all &quot;themed&quot; now.  Basically, each pack of Lego only builds one thing, and even more deplorable, each package has ASSEMBLY INSTRUCTIONS.  Blasphemy!<br>
<br>
So who the heck wants to take the time to invent a game world that people have to visualize when you can become a slave to Sony's vision?  <br>
<br>
Hopefully things will change.<br>
